1
00:00:04,640 --> 00:00:10,270
What’s real and what’s not real
about all these things

2
00:00:10,270 --> 00:00:12,029
and self-expression?

3
00:00:12,029 --> 00:00:15,279
[Advertising | Humanistic Slogans]

4
00:00:15,479 --> 00:00:19,173
Even in a secular sense,

5
00:00:19,173 --> 00:00:27,773
artists, writers, musicians, 
different types of artists,

6
00:00:27,773 --> 00:00:31,630
they talk about finding 
their own voice

7
00:00:31,630 --> 00:00:36,268
under the layers and layers 
of cliché,

8
00:00:36,268 --> 00:00:40,921
of clichéd artistic expression.

9
00:00:40,921 --> 00:00:44,524
They talk about
“trying to find your own voice”.

10
00:00:44,524 --> 00:00:49,798
Even they know, they’ve written books:
“The Anatomy of Influence”,

11
00:00:49,798 --> 00:00:52,123
how you’re under the influence of those,

12
00:00:52,123 --> 00:00:55,909
who thought and
expressed ideas before you.

13
00:00:55,909 --> 00:00:59,704
So they’re talking about how to find 
your “true” artistic voice,

14
00:00:59,704 --> 00:01:02,862
you know, your self-expression.

15
00:01:02,862 --> 00:01:05,227
So even they recognise that;

16
00:01:05,227 --> 00:01:09,905
they know, for the most part, 
what people express

17
00:01:09,905 --> 00:01:16,263
is just their regurgitating 
what they’ve heard from others.

18
00:01:16,263 --> 00:01:19,643
As Guru Mahārāj once said, 
what he liked about Saraswati Ṭhākur,

19
00:01:19,643 --> 00:01:21,783
one of the things he liked about him,

20
00:01:21,783 --> 00:01:25,263
he was not vomiting
what he heard from others.

21
00:01:25,263 --> 00:01:30,905
So, for the most part, people are
just vomiting what they’ve heard.

22
00:01:30,905 --> 00:01:33,809
And where do they hear it?

23
00:01:33,809 --> 00:01:38,737
A famous playwright, Arthur Miller,

24
00:01:38,737 --> 00:01:42,602
when playwrights were important people—

25
00:01:42,602 --> 00:01:45,502
it was around the 1940s, 50’s,

26
00:01:45,502 --> 00:01:51,663
when Americans and Europeans, 
particularly,

27
00:01:51,663 --> 00:02:00,945
looked to playwrights as
the interpreters of life,

28
00:02:00,945 --> 00:02:04,392
what’s important,
and such things as that,

29
00:02:04,392 --> 00:02:08,143
and they would think that they present
in their plays the big questions,

30
00:02:08,143 --> 00:02:13,111
the things we should understand about 
life and existence and how to proceed,

31
00:02:13,111 --> 00:02:16,742
so really they occupied the position 
of, like, the ‘kavi’,

32
00:02:16,742 --> 00:02:23,941
the poet in the Sanskrit sense,
the interpreters of reality.

33
00:02:23,941 --> 00:02:27,703
But this man, he wrote his famous play,
“Death of a Salesman”,

34
00:02:27,703 --> 00:02:34,265
and they keep running it, but
they interviewed him a few years back

35
00:02:34,265 --> 00:02:40,550
because now this art form
is virtually vanished.

36
00:02:40,550 --> 00:02:45,306
So they’re thinking he’s arguably one of
the greatest playwrights of the 20th century,

37
00:02:45,306 --> 00:02:48,488
and “what do you have to say, 
sir, about it all?”

38
00:02:48,488 --> 00:02:52,281
And he said, quite simply and frankly,

39
00:02:52,281 --> 00:03:00,320
he said, “Today, most people 
get their concepts about reality,

40
00:03:00,320 --> 00:03:06,480
or life, or existence, from advertising.”

41
00:03:07,615 --> 00:03:11,859
He said, “That's where 
they get their ideas.”

42
00:03:11,859 --> 00:03:18,400
So we see, people see ads,
and what are the ads?

43
00:03:18,400 --> 00:03:26,574
Basically, they’re 
humanistic sloganeering.

44
00:03:26,574 --> 00:03:36,144
Levi’s “Go forth!”, “You are you!”,
“Go forth!”… Humanistic poetry.

45
00:03:36,144 --> 00:03:43,244
Nike’s “Just do it!”, 
L’Oreal’s “I’m worth it!”

46
00:03:43,244 --> 00:03:47,984
It’s all humanism;
they’re humanistic slogans

47
00:03:47,984 --> 00:03:52,671
that basically have pushed
the notion, the concept,

48
00:03:52,671 --> 00:03:55,634
the idea of God out of the picture

49
00:03:55,634 --> 00:04:01,427
and put man as the centre 
and measure of all things.

50
00:04:01,427 --> 00:04:06,982
As Solzhenitsyn pointed out, 
“Man, with all of his innumerable defects,

51
00:04:06,982 --> 00:04:11,092
he’ll be the measure 
of the value of all things.”

52
00:04:11,092 --> 00:04:14,680
That’s humanism in a nutshell.

53
00:04:14,680 --> 00:04:19,810
He calls it “the disastrous deviation 
of the Enlightenment”,

54
00:04:19,810 --> 00:04:21,757
of Enlightenment thinkers.

55
00:04:21,757 --> 00:04:25,561
So that’s the irony,

56
00:04:25,561 --> 00:04:34,023
that this sort of dense darkness 
is being called Enlightenment:

57
00:04:34,023 --> 00:04:39,183
“There is no God. There’s no need for God.
You are God.”

